  "prompt": "What do you think about ISRO working on space shuttle instead of building one like Soyuz when space shuttle is clearly expensive and not safe?",
  "response": "ISRO (Indian Space Research Organisation) has actually been more focused on developing its own Reusable Launch Vehicle (RLV) technology rather than directly copying either the Space Shuttle or Soyuz designs. Their approach aims to create a more cost-effective and safer alternative. \n\nThe RLV-TD (Technology Demonstrator) project is designed to develop indigenous reusable launch vehicle technologies, learning from previous shuttle experiences while trying to avoid their high operational costs. ISRO's design considers:\n\n1. Lower development and operational costs\n2. Improved safety mechanisms\n3. Modular design\n4. Partial reusability\n5. Indigenous technology development\n\nThey're not trying to replicate the complete Space Shuttle, but rather create a more efficient, scaled-down version suited to India's specific space exploration needs and technological capabilities.\n\nThe Soyuz, while reliable, has limitations in payload capacity and reusability, which ISRO wants to address with their RLV approach. Their strategy seems more pragmatic - learning from international experiences while developing a solution tailored to India's requirements.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any specific aspect of ISRO's space shuttle/RLV development?",
